HEADWORD: Cothurn
<hw>Co"thurn</hw> <pr>(k?"th?rn)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>cothurnus</ets>, Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/. Cf. <er>Cothurnus</er>.]</ety>
<def>A buskin anciently used by tragic actors on the stage; hence,
tragedy in general.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The moment had arrived when it was thought that the mask and the
<qex>cothurn</qex> might be assumed with effect.</q>
<rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cothurnated</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Cothurnate</ent>⟦br⟧
